WEBVTT

00:00.162 --> 00:01.383
and please be seated.

00:08.331 --> 00:12.396
This morning we consider our scripture text from Psalm 36.

00:13.877 --> 00:19.023
Psalm 36, and if you are turning in a Pew Bible, you can find that on page 465.

00:19.063 --> 00:21.526
I would invite you to turn with me there.

00:22.447 --> 00:27.072
Before we read our Psalm this morning, let's go to the Lord together in prayer.

00:27.092 --> 00:28.594
Would you pray with me, please?

00:30.658 --> 00:35.845
O father, we ask that you would open our eyes that we may see wondrous things in your word.

00:35.865 --> 00:40.171
O Lord, as we gaze upon your steadfast love.

00:41.573 --> 00:52.929
O Lord, as we consider your word to us, your promise to us in Psalm 36, we ask that you would shore up our faith, O Lord, that you would strengthen us, that you would fan the embers within us.

00:54.211 --> 00:59.538
O God, that you would cause us to rejoice in the one in whom we find our righteousness, which is Christ.

01:00.866 --> 01:07.635
And so Father, we pray that you would indeed give us ears to hear and eyes to see Christ this morning.

01:08.075 --> 01:08.836
Would you bless us?

01:09.957 --> 01:12.280
And Father, I pray and ask these things in Jesus' name.

01:13.021 --> 01:13.362
Amen.

01:14.403 --> 01:20.751
It's a Psalm 36, God's Word, holy, inspired, and errant, perfect, infallible.

01:21.892 --> 01:22.894
Let us give ear.

01:26.899 --> 01:29.522
To the choir master of David,

01:30.210 --> 01:31.351
the servant of the Lord.

01:34.094 --> 01:39.461
Transgression speaks to the wicked deep in his heart.

01:40.702 --> 01:43.345
There is no fear of God before his eyes.

01:44.947 --> 01:49.492
For he flatters himself in his own eyes that his iniquity cannot be found out and hated.

01:49.512 --> 01:53.617
The words of his mouth are trouble and deceit.

01:55.038 --> 01:58.162
He has ceased to act wisely and do good

01:58.626 --> 02:00.909
He plots trouble while on his bed.

02:01.010 --> 02:03.453
He sets himself in a way that is not good.

02:03.513 --> 02:06.037
He does not reject evil.

02:08.421 --> 02:13.549
Your steadfast love, O Lord, extends to the heavens.

02:14.350 --> 02:16.373
Your faithfulness to the clouds.

02:17.375 --> 02:19.478
Your righteousness is like the mountains of God.

02:19.538 --> 02:25.107
Your judgments are like the great deep man and beast you save, O Lord.

02:25.167 --> 02:27.410
How precious

02:27.778 --> 02:34.548
is your steadfast love, O God, the children of mankind take refuge in the shadow of your wings.

02:35.770 --> 02:43.361
They feast on the abundance of your house, and you give them drink from the river of your delights, for with you is the fountain of life.

02:44.563 --> 02:47.687
In your light, do we see light?

02:49.070 --> 02:57.522
O continue your steadfast love to those who know you, and your righteousness to the upright of heart, let not the foot of arrogance come upon me.

02:58.146 --> 03:00.168
Or the hand of the wicked drive me away.

03:00.228 --> 03:03.431
There the evil doers lie fallen.

03:04.312 --> 03:07.856
They are thrust down, unable to rise.

03:09.798 --> 03:12.380
This is the word of the Lord.

03:13.301 --> 03:14.242
Thanks be to God.

03:17.045 --> 03:18.847
David here considers the heart of man.

03:19.107 --> 03:23.611
And there's a sense in which he's calling upon us to ask this question.

03:23.671 --> 03:26.354
If you could take your heart out

03:26.722 --> 03:28.785
And you could look at it.

03:29.767 --> 03:30.869
How would you respond?

03:31.730 --> 03:33.413
And what would you say?

03:33.473 --> 03:40.484
Now, you may be anticipating this, but I don't mean this anatomically.

03:41.506 --> 03:49.639
Maybe some of you have spent time with an EKG or an echocardiogram or even a specialized CT.

03:49.679 --> 03:53.906
I know I have seen my own heart, but what

03:54.082 --> 04:04.272
The author speaks of here regarding the heart is not that organ that beats and pumps blood through us, but he means of the spiritual heart.

04:05.693 --> 04:12.179
And Sinclair Ferguson writing for Ligonier Ministries gives us what he calls a catechism of the heart.

04:13.060 --> 04:14.161
He asks this question.

04:14.501 --> 04:15.902
He says, what is the heart?

04:16.383 --> 04:17.444
And he answers this way.

04:17.484 --> 04:24.050
He says, the heart is the central core and drive of my life intellectually

04:24.610 --> 04:35.305
meaning it moves my mind, affectionately, meaning it shapes my soul, and totally it provides the energy for my living.

04:36.567 --> 04:42.436
The heart is that central core which drives my life intellectually, affectionately and totally.

04:42.716 --> 04:46.021
The heart is what drives my very body itself.

04:47.363 --> 04:52.530
You've ever seen or maybe you remember the commercials with that Duracell pink bunny.

04:53.666 --> 04:57.791
what happens, but it just keeps going and going and going.

04:57.831 --> 04:59.433
Well, why?

04:59.513 --> 05:04.059
And according to their advertising, it's because it's powered by a Duracell battery.

05:04.920 --> 05:08.804
But in some ways, for every man, woman, and child, that's what our heart is.

05:08.844 --> 05:14.351
It's what makes us and keeps us going and going and going as we are sustained by the power of God.

05:15.573 --> 05:20.018
But just because we function doesn't mean that we function

05:20.098 --> 05:26.145
well or function with righteousness or function with holiness or function as God intended us.

05:26.866 --> 05:29.629
In fact, we don't because we were all fallen and sin.

05:29.689 --> 05:42.062
Our heart is the source of wickedness and our hearts must be changed as the children have considered downstairs before we can believe in God and go to heaven.

05:43.144 --> 05:45.026
We have a diseased heart from birth.

05:46.027 --> 05:48.850
And so Ferguson writes to answer the second question.

05:49.698 --> 05:57.309
And so I think it is important for us to see our hearts in perspective, for we do have a diseased heart from birth.

05:58.672 --> 06:04.901
And what I think David does here in Psalm 36 is he considers the heart from a realistic perspective.

06:06.223 --> 06:08.787
Notice that David begins this psalm with the wicked.

06:09.948 --> 06:14.335
Oftentimes psalms like this end with addressing the wicked rather than the beginning.

06:14.696 --> 06:18.962
And so David, I think here, sets the stage for us to truly love

06:19.138 --> 06:21.701
and cherish the steadfast love of God.

06:22.362 --> 06:25.086
Consider what he says of the wicked here at its outset.

06:25.146 --> 06:29.792
First he notices he or he speaks of our transgressions or our sins.

06:30.313 --> 06:34.298
Our breaking God's laws and commands tells us something about the heart.

06:35.600 --> 06:38.243
Our sin is a symptom of a greater problem.

06:39.104 --> 06:46.514
Right if your eyes are watering or your nose is running and you can't stop sneezing and your head feels stuffy

06:47.458 --> 06:54.188
At least in South Carolina, all you have to do is look around at the haze that is everywhere and realize that you were probably dealing with some kind of hay fever.

06:55.230 --> 06:55.711
How do I do?

06:57.534 --> 07:02.361
And our sin tells us that deep in our heart, there is no fear of God before our eyes.

07:03.122 --> 07:05.045
This fear isn't being afraid.

07:05.105 --> 07:13.498
It's not that terror from an abusive, desperate, or tyrant, but this fear is an overwhelming sense of in confronting the holiness of God.

07:13.859 --> 07:15.922
What David is saying is that our sin

07:16.194 --> 07:29.389
This regards a holy God who is zealous for his own glory, who is full of mercy and grace, and because of his steadfast love and faithfulness, he has rescued and redeemed the people for himself.

07:29.409 --> 07:33.753
So fearing God comes from a spirit-filled acknowledgment and confrontation with the gospel.

07:35.095 --> 07:40.080
Those that send David says devalue and toss aside the reality of all that God is.

07:40.921 --> 07:41.983
The wicked, he says.

07:43.504 --> 07:45.106
But second, notice

07:45.474 --> 07:47.817
David says, how the wicked come to this point.

07:49.299 --> 07:52.803
These are the accompanying symptoms of our fallen nature.

07:53.423 --> 07:58.610
The problem is, right, that the diagnosis is there is no fear of God before their eyes.

07:59.711 --> 08:01.473
But it reveals itself in a few different ways.

08:01.513 --> 08:04.857
In verse two, he says, he flatters himself in his own eyes.

08:05.578 --> 08:07.500
That his iniquity cannot be found out and hated.

08:08.501 --> 08:12.306
He thinks himself to be more righteous than he is.

08:12.738 --> 08:15.563
This is the beginning of what we call hypocrisy.

08:16.625 --> 08:25.681
What that means is that we see what is wrong in others, but not in ourselves, or we behold the speck in others' eyes and ignore the plank in ours.

08:26.662 --> 08:33.234
The wicked man, according to David, is blinded by his own self-satisfaction, that it's like he puts lipstick on a pig,

08:34.466 --> 08:38.450
He can't name his own sin or see his own condemnation before God.

08:38.850 --> 08:44.036
David says not only is he blinded, but the words of his mouth are trouble and deceit.

08:44.336 --> 08:46.438
He has ceased to act wisely and do good.

08:46.498 --> 08:53.145
It is clear from how he speaks and what he says and how he gossips and cuts down others and spreads falsehoods.

08:54.586 --> 08:55.968
But they eventually give up the charade.

08:57.369 --> 09:02.194
They give up pretending to do good and turn and to find their rest in doing evil.

09:02.978 --> 09:14.599
Plotting even upon their pillow, David says, some ways David describes a spiral from cherishing the appearance of righteousness to loving wickedness.

09:15.981 --> 09:19.027
Now, I promise you there's a point here, okay?

09:20.069 --> 09:27.602
I think what he's done is just described to us the nature of our own hearts, of yours and of mine.

09:28.290 --> 09:39.741
If we could take our heart out and look at it apart from the grace of God and Christ's finished work and its application to us by the Holy Spirit, brothers, sisters, this is our path.

09:41.042 --> 09:50.452
This is your trajectory, that proverbial spiraling from the appearance of righteousness to the loving wickedness.

09:52.253 --> 09:56.978
But David has good news for you and me this morning and it doesn't have anything to do with us.

09:57.506 --> 09:58.868
but has everything to do with God.

09:59.830 --> 10:02.714
The wicked may chart their own way.

10:03.135 --> 10:11.888
The wicked may chart their own way, but first what I want you to see this morning is the righteous know the steadfast love of the Lord is perfect.

10:11.908 --> 10:16.315
The righteous know firstly that the steadfast love of the Lord is perfect.

10:17.617 --> 10:21.844
This first bit of good news is one that we need to remind ourselves of and do so often.

10:21.904 --> 10:24.788
The steadfast love of the Lord is unending.

10:25.169 --> 10:25.970
It is great.

10:26.210 --> 10:27.892
And it is the source of this grace.

10:27.952 --> 10:30.856
It doesn't come from within, but it comes from without.

10:31.738 --> 10:36.665
We look outside of ourselves to find the overwhelming mercy and steadfast love of God.

10:37.125 --> 10:38.187
It comes from on high.

10:39.408 --> 10:48.761
But because this mercy and grace flow from our God in heaven, it is as unending and it is as eternal and perfect as God Himself is.

10:50.183 --> 10:52.146
Your mercy, O Lord, is in the heavens.

10:52.322 --> 10:55.045
your faithfulness extends to the clouds.

10:55.345 --> 10:57.027
It's unsearchable, David tells us.

10:57.287 --> 10:58.629
We'll never see its end.

10:59.009 --> 11:01.412
It is unending and it is infinite.

11:02.793 --> 11:12.944
Think through the simple fact, for example, that it's only been in the last 60 years or so that man has left Earth's atmosphere.

11:14.646 --> 11:21.714
The Soviet, Yuri Geregan, probably butchering that name, he circled Earth outside of orbit for roughly

11:21.826 --> 11:24.830
108 minutes before reentry.

11:25.871 --> 11:32.000
And in that moment, we were no more able to reach and know the ends of the universe than we are today.

11:32.901 --> 11:44.837
Despite moon landings, space programs, telescopes and satellites, rovers and deep space probes, they all reveal something to us and make something extremely and abundantly clear.

11:45.698 --> 11:51.506
They help show us that the universe is all the more unknowable and seemingly unending the farther we go.

11:53.314 --> 11:58.962
would we seek to penetrate the height and glory of God's steadfast love?

11:59.002 --> 12:02.488
We see that this is a fitting description of God's grace and mercy.

12:02.708 --> 12:14.906
We find ourselves under an infinite expanse, and the more and more we grow in our understanding, even in our own personal experience of God's love for us, we're left speechless.

12:16.148 --> 12:19.072
Or maybe we can only respond as the psalmist.

12:21.375 --> 12:23.218
I think a mark of sanctification

12:23.522 --> 12:30.192
is not merely learning new things about God, but coming to a realization of just how little we comprehend the things of God.

12:31.393 --> 12:33.697
It's a sign we're being sanctified in our minds.

12:34.498 --> 12:37.783
And yet again, we find that his judgments here are like the great deep.

12:38.484 --> 12:45.714
And here it could be that there is a reference to his judgments against man, or it could be a reference to the Scriptures as the judgments.

12:46.210 --> 12:53.180
But either way, it would just seem that there is a relation to the great deep or the sea that there is a particular burden placed on this aspect.

12:53.200 --> 12:53.881
It's weighty.

12:55.563 --> 12:59.749
If we think about how the ocean is viewed in the Old Testament, it's a frightening place.

13:00.711 --> 13:02.714
It's where the winds blow and the waves churn.

13:02.754 --> 13:05.217
Think of the water's ability to swallow ships.

13:05.678 --> 13:09.624
Think of the remote nature of sailing, how quickly a squall can appear.

13:09.644 --> 13:14.130
Maybe you've been on a cruise ship in the middle of the night and you're struck by just how dark it is at sea.

13:15.458 --> 13:17.720
Think of the terror that befell the seafarers.

13:17.820 --> 13:24.527
When Jonah was setting sail and running from the Lord's command, there was a healthy fear in the deep, in the days of David.

13:26.489 --> 13:28.371
But this is the other side of the coin, right?

13:28.971 --> 13:33.456
The revelation of God and his word is, and his rendering of his judgment.

13:33.496 --> 13:34.757
It is, it is perfect.

13:36.719 --> 13:37.700
You can put it a different way.

13:37.740 --> 13:43.826
Who can argue with God and try as the wicked man might?

13:44.482 --> 13:46.404
But who can disagree with the Lord?

13:47.084 --> 13:49.747
Who can fathom and comprehend the mystery of His will?

13:52.209 --> 13:54.271
Let's try to bring this into perspective a little bit here.

13:55.853 --> 13:58.795
Sometimes it feels as if we arrive under God's providence.

14:00.357 --> 14:10.787
Perhaps even from day to day or year to year or season to season, we know times of peace and times of hardship, times of abundance even.

14:11.187 --> 14:14.450
Sometimes the waters are glassy and calm

14:15.362 --> 14:19.327
and that others, the waves, rage, and the storms set in.

14:19.387 --> 14:28.158
And we wonder at just what the Lord is doing, we try to pierce the veil of the mystery of God's will, and we most often can't put the pieces together.

14:29.219 --> 14:30.881
I don't want you to hear the words of Charles Spurgeon.

14:30.901 --> 14:35.707
He says this, as the deep, or the sea, mirrors the sky.

14:36.949 --> 14:44.178
So the mercy of the Lord is to be seen reflected in all the arrangements of His government on earth.

14:45.346 --> 14:54.761
And over the profound depth, the covenant rainbow casts its arch of comfort for the Lord is faithful in all that He does.

14:56.083 --> 15:05.838
You see, the steadfast love of the Lord permeates all of our life in church, whether you're in a season of peace or tranquility or storm or a white-capped swell.

15:06.899 --> 15:08.722
God's love for you is perfect.

15:09.698 --> 15:13.462
And you realize that we've been given a pattern for understanding God's providence in your life.

15:13.842 --> 15:19.988
We might be short-sighted in the haze of God's infinitude, but he has surely revealed his nature to us by way of the cross.

15:21.269 --> 15:24.812
And surely he who did not spare his own son but gave him up for us all.

15:25.213 --> 15:28.676
How will he not also with him graciously give us all things?

15:29.817 --> 15:39.186
The love of the cross and the empty tomb serve the believer to not only accomplish salvation, but to be the way through which we view God and our circumstance.

15:39.458 --> 15:45.447
When life happens to us, don't lose view of the cross.

15:49.012 --> 15:57.225
Secondly, in contrast to the wicked, the righteous know the steadfast love of the Lord is priceless.

15:58.266 --> 16:00.910
The righteous know the steadfast love of the Lord is priceless.

16:01.651 --> 16:03.654
Verse perfect, now, priceless.

16:05.036 --> 16:08.722
The wicked may chart their own way, but the righteous know again the steadfast love of the Lord

16:08.802 --> 16:10.144
is priceless.

16:10.184 --> 16:21.299
And this marks a shift in this song because it turns and transitions from beholding the Lord's steadfast love for what it is to raising the question, what is it to you?

16:23.221 --> 16:24.123
What is it to you?

16:25.304 --> 16:33.255
And the aim here is the believer's heart restored and beating for the sake of Christ and His glory and the proclamation of the gospel.

16:33.315 --> 16:38.482
David writes in verse 7, how precious is your steadfast love, O God.

16:38.882 --> 16:42.345
the children of mankind take refuge in the shadow of your wings."

16:42.846 --> 16:48.832
And believers, this is a glorious covenant language that is yours for he is your God and you are his people.

16:49.092 --> 17:02.125
This is a reminder of his faithfulness to you, a picture of the care of a mother showing love to her young and care for her young, the comfort and protection against those enemies that would seek and destroy.

17:03.486 --> 17:07.090
But notice that not only is this steadfast love of the Lord precious to God's children,

17:07.458 --> 17:10.162
But the quality of such love is described.

17:10.182 --> 17:12.626
The provision is great.

17:13.547 --> 17:19.497
They feast on the abundance of your house and you give them drink from the river of your delights.

17:19.837 --> 17:22.962
We get our fill and it is unending.

17:23.443 --> 17:28.350
Life itself springs forth from the Lord and we live and we walk in that light.

17:30.313 --> 17:35.922
It seems to be that what David has in mind here is the idea of covenant communion.

17:36.450 --> 17:45.264
the feeding upon, and being refreshed in God's love, not with food, but himself, and worship even.

17:45.765 --> 17:47.527
Even what we're going to do soon here at the table.

17:49.971 --> 17:58.665
There's a time, Meg and I, for an anniversary, we're gifted a gift card to a Brazilian steakhouse.

17:59.646 --> 18:00.908
Maybe you've been to one before.

18:00.948 --> 18:04.594
If you've not been to one before, let me tell you it's a glorious place.

18:04.962 --> 18:12.554
where people where the smells are amazing and people walk around with unending roasted meat on swords.

18:13.315 --> 18:17.141
And all they want to do is come by you and shave off a piece and give you as much as you can eat.

18:18.282 --> 18:26.916
And since then, and it was such a great experience that I can't consider God's abundance apart from a Brazilian steakhouse.

18:29.900 --> 18:33.586
Not to belittle the Lord's covenant love and care for us,

18:33.954 --> 18:43.889
But you can imagine, can you imagine feasting upon the Lord's goodness and his kindness toward us in Christ until we feel as if we will burst and we will pop and it never ends.

18:43.909 --> 18:45.251
It never ceases.

18:45.271 --> 18:52.402
The Brazilian steakhouse may be a picture of abundance and honestly excess.

18:53.090 --> 19:01.218
But nonetheless, this idea of satisfaction and abundance is what drives the believer to find the Lord's steadfast love priceless and precious.

19:01.558 --> 19:04.241
He will not let you wither in waste away.

19:05.722 --> 19:07.884
But He will meet every one of your needs in Christ.

19:08.825 --> 19:10.006
And so I ask a question again.

19:10.046 --> 19:15.992
Do you find the Lord's steadfast love priceless and precious?

19:17.033 --> 19:22.098
Because the Lord in His love for us is only as valuable to you as you cherish it and know it intimately.

19:22.274 --> 19:26.179
And if not, could it be that you're looking to fill your souls with something that will never satisfy?

19:27.461 --> 19:38.374
If I were to leave my children's diets up to themselves, they might feast upon ice cream and M&Ms and lollipops and chips.

19:39.155 --> 19:40.177
But you're the problem with that.

19:40.237 --> 19:44.682
It may taste sweet, but it will not provide for them the nourishment and the nurturing they need.

19:44.722 --> 19:47.506
In fact, it will leave them feeling ill and terrible.

19:49.026 --> 19:54.313
But the point is this, could it be that our souls are restless and weary because we have not feasted upon the abundance of God's goodness?

19:54.694 --> 20:03.405
That we have not worshiped Him and ascribed to Him glory and praise that we have not been known the overwhelming satisfaction of our sin being covered.

20:04.006 --> 20:08.011
Our God who is near grace and mercy undeserved.

20:09.333 --> 20:15.922
You see, His love is not precious often because we think we have no need to take refuge under His knee under His wings.

20:16.514 --> 20:21.542
We have no need to feast upon the abundance of his house nor drink from the river of his delights.

20:22.924 --> 20:26.870
And the life and light as much do not reside in us or shine upon us."

20:28.392 --> 20:36.484
See, the wicked man delights on himself, but the righteous man delights in the Lord because it is through Christ and his finished work alone that wicked men are made righteous.

20:38.006 --> 20:40.530
And you realize that's why we gather for worship, don't you?

20:41.218 --> 20:43.201
It's why we do what we do every Lord's day.

20:43.261 --> 20:47.106
It is our devotion to our Lord and their response to our Savior.

20:47.166 --> 20:52.714
It is the means to which we are nourished and nurtured and satisfied as we feast upon the means of grace.

20:52.734 --> 21:00.404
It would Christ and His work should become all the more satisfying to you and would you rejoice in the steadfast love of the Lord.

21:02.427 --> 21:10.738
Thirdly and lastly, we consider it is perfect, priceless, but is also

21:11.010 --> 21:14.114
The righteous know the steadfast love of the Lord is sure.

21:16.277 --> 21:18.620
You notice at the end here David gives himself over to prayer.

21:19.642 --> 21:29.315
In some ways this is the synthesis of these verses and these last verses are a plea resting upon the very promises that make the Lord's love steadfast to begin with.

21:30.277 --> 21:31.598
It's an appeal to his faithfulness.

21:32.500 --> 21:34.442
This is what Spurgeon says of prayer.

21:34.903 --> 21:40.050
He says the best praying man is the man who is most believingly meaning by faith

21:40.258 --> 21:44.923
the man who most believingly familiar with the promises of God.

21:44.983 --> 21:53.131
After all, prayer is nothing but taking God's promises to him and saying to him, do as thou hast said.

21:54.452 --> 21:57.695
Prayer is the promise utilized.

21:59.117 --> 22:03.241
Prayer which is not based on a promise has no true foundation.

22:03.981 --> 22:08.626
The best praying man is a man who believingly is familiar with the promises of God.

22:09.474 --> 22:17.827
And so David appeals to the Lord, asking that he might continue his steadfast love to those who know him and your righteousness to the upright and heart.

22:19.249 --> 22:24.177
Our satisfaction in the Lord is directly correlating to how well we know his promises.

22:25.399 --> 22:26.841
Our assurance is not, as R.C.

22:26.861 --> 22:30.467
Sproul has said, that we hold tightly to him, but that he holds tightly to us.

22:31.669 --> 22:37.778
And so David's prayer is not wishful thinking, it's not potential possibility, but it's a sure and certain thing.

22:38.626 --> 22:44.435
this trust in the promises of God, which seek to pray them back to Him, this is the essence of faith.

22:44.956 --> 22:50.845
Or as the author of Hebrews says, the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen.

22:52.347 --> 22:54.030
This is not how Hebrews 11 begins.

22:56.173 --> 23:06.930
And if you were to walk through the Hall of Faith in Hebrews 11 and consider each entry, the story of every man and every woman was that there was a sure hope in the Lord, a trusting of God's promises.

23:08.386 --> 23:11.832
And yet this song ends on a realistic note.

23:12.954 --> 23:21.108
Again, something like the synthesis of both, the consideration of the wicked and the steadfast of the Lord, David says, and he prays, let not the foot of arrogance come upon me.

23:21.148 --> 23:24.473
Nor the hand of the wicked drive me away.

23:24.513 --> 23:27.078
They are the evil doers life fallen.

23:27.478 --> 23:29.502
They are thrust down, unable to rise.

23:30.784 --> 23:34.290
Our holding on to God's promises is not without its trial and test, friends.

23:35.202 --> 23:45.861
And so this prayer uses the steadfast love of the Lord as a lens through which the author and by way us are to see the world around us and live accordingly.

23:47.183 --> 23:48.465
This is a prayer of protection.

23:49.627 --> 24:00.306
Unless we think that life is all sunshine and rainbows and butterflies, this prayer is offered that the steadfast love of the Lord would remain in the face of wicked opposition.

24:00.674 --> 24:02.897
This is putting the promises of God to work.

24:03.218 --> 24:15.417
And just as one plus one plus one equals three, so does relying upon God's promises produce a sum of knowledge of the Lord's steadfast love.

24:15.437 --> 24:18.562
But what is this opposition David receives?

24:20.905 --> 24:24.831
What if it's slander against your character and name for how you pursue the Lord in faithfulness?

24:26.033 --> 24:29.298
Making false claims or misconstruing what you've done or what you've said?

24:30.146 --> 24:36.152
What if it's pressure to silence the Lord and quiet His words as it's read and preached and studied and proclaimed?

24:37.473 --> 24:40.816
What if it's opposition from within, not just without, but in here?

24:41.297 --> 24:45.221
Sometimes the wicked man's heart becomes known and it's revealed.

24:45.581 --> 24:54.029
But mostly as new covenant Christians, while this should apply to worldly opposition, I think what you see the great wicked enemy is Satan himself.

24:55.951 --> 24:58.994
And can't we pray this psalm of him who longs for his

24:59.138 --> 25:00.700
foot of arrogance to come upon me?

25:01.761 --> 25:04.204
Whose hand longs to drive away the righteous?

25:05.645 --> 25:09.830
You get this image of Satan wanting to place his foot upon your neck and to take you and throw you aside.

25:10.771 --> 25:17.779
Your destruction and the silencing of God is his desire, but can't we also like David who draws attention to the state of the wicked?

25:17.820 --> 25:20.983
There they are fallen and thrust down unable to rise.

25:21.724 --> 25:22.905
Can we stay the same of Satan?

25:24.107 --> 25:26.930
Isn't it Satan of whom Jesus says in Luke 10,

25:27.074 --> 25:29.378
I saw him fall like lightning.

25:30.860 --> 25:34.646
His house, the strong man has been bound.

25:35.707 --> 25:44.741
His power has been broken, and those who Christ has called to himself have been granted authority over all the power of the enemy, and nothing shall hurt you.

25:48.186 --> 25:51.792
Beloved, take heart this day that God speaks truth to you.

25:53.254 --> 25:55.858
Don't fall to the lies.

25:57.154 --> 25:58.015
of the deceiver.

25:59.778 --> 26:01.560
And so this prayer has been fulfilled in Christ.

26:02.481 --> 26:07.068
And as Christians, we can pray this in some ways with more assurance and certainly the David.

26:07.769 --> 26:16.541
It's the same faithful God to which we trust and hope, but it's a glorious thing to see what we have always been promised has come to pass in Jesus Christ.

26:17.182 --> 26:18.344
Satan has been defeated.

26:18.684 --> 26:20.567
The Lord presently rules and reigns.

26:20.987 --> 26:25.874
And we know that despite our own sin, despite those enemies of God, despite Satan himself,

26:26.082 --> 26:30.910
The steadfast love the Lord is unending, unfading, and unfailing.

26:31.911 --> 26:33.314
And we know this through Jesus Christ.

26:34.255 --> 26:35.517
And would it be that you would know Him more?

26:35.658 --> 26:36.579
Would you seek Him more?

26:36.599 --> 26:37.641
Would you worship Him more?

26:37.681 --> 26:38.723
Would you follow Him more?

26:39.384 --> 26:40.445
Would you love Him more?

26:41.467 --> 26:44.913
And like that in Him, we find our righteousness.

26:46.115 --> 26:47.096
Let's pray together.

26:51.784 --> 26:53.106
Oh Father, we thank You.

26:54.914 --> 27:00.062
for your love is sure, it is steadfast, and it is unending.

27:02.185 --> 27:18.450
Father, we ask that when we would doubt that love for us, that we would have our hearts and minds cast to the cross, where we see love on display, and find our hope is as alive as Christ is raised from the dead.

27:20.386 --> 27:26.195
And so, Lord, we pray that you would cause us to reflect upon and to dwell upon and delight in your steadfast love of the morn.

27:26.275 --> 27:32.365
And Father, might it be that we would believe upon you, be strengthened and follow after you.

27:33.307 --> 27:34.388
In Christ's name, we pray.

27:35.029 --> 27:35.330
Amen.

27:36.451 --> 27:41.199
Let's stand together and sing Jesus' light blood and righteousness.

